---
// DAY-207. Cookie consent banner for GA4 + Clarity.
//
// Design constraints
//
//   - Default state is *no analytics loaded*. Analytics never run
//     before consent — UK ICO + EU EDPB guidance, and the same
//     posture as the rest of the product.
//
//   - Two buttons, equal visual weight. Pre-selecting "Accept" by
//     making it visually dominant (a saturated brand-coloured
//     button next to a dim ghost "Decline") is non-compliant
//     under recent EDPB enforcement guidance. Both options must
//     be a single click and equally reachable.
//
//   - Decline is sticky. A user who declines today shouldn't see
//     this banner on every visit. We persist both Accept and
//     Decline as durable choices in localStorage; only an
//     explicit "Cookie preferences" action in the footer
//     (`#cookie-preferences`) reopens the banner.
//
//   - Banner is keyboard-accessible. role="dialog", aria-labelled,
//     focus is moved to the Accept button on first show, the
//     dialog is closeable via Escape (treated as Decline — least
//     surprising default for an Escape key on a "do you allow X"
//     dialog).
//
//   - No FOUC. The banner CSS is inlined into the rendered HTML
//     so there is no one-frame visual jitter on first paint, and
//     the banner is hidden by default (`hidden` attribute) so
//     returning visitors who already chose never see it flash.
//
//   - No layout impact. The banner is `position: fixed` at the
//     bottom; nothing on the page reflows when it appears or
//     disappears. Combined with not being part of the document
//     reading order until shown, this means CLS stays at zero.
//
// Why a single localStorage key, not an in-page form
//
//   The simplest schema that captures the consent decision is
//   `dayseam-cookie-consent-v1 = "accepted" | "declined"`. The
//   `-v1` suffix is intentional: if a future change broadens
//   what we collect (say we add a third tracker), the key bumps
//   to `-v2` and stale Accept choices stop applying — effectively
//   re-prompting users. Versioning the key from day one is the
//   cheapest way to keep that future option open.
//
// Why no "necessary / preferences / analytics / marketing" four-
// tier UI like Cookiebot
//
//   The site has zero essential cookies. Every cookie this site
//   would ever set is non-essential analytics. A four-tier
//   checkbox UI for one category is theatre — a binary
//   accept/decline is more honest and less to maintain.
//
// Reset hook
//
//   The footer renders an anchor with `href="#cookie-preferences"`.
//   The inline script below listens for clicks on that anchor,
//   clears the storage entry, and re-shows the banner so a user
//   can change their mind. (Reload not required.)
---

<aside
  id="cookie-consent"
  role="dialog"
  aria-labelledby="cookie-consent-title"
  aria-describedby="cookie-consent-body"
  hidden
  class="fixed inset-x-4 bottom-4 z-50 mx-auto max-w-2xl rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-charcoal-900/95 p-5 shadow-2xl backdrop-blur sm:inset-x-auto sm:left-1/2 sm:-translate-x-1/2"
>
  <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:items-start">
    <div class="flex-1 text-sm">
      <p
        id="cookie-consent-title"
        class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-strand-gold"
      >
        Cookies
      </p>
      <p id="cookie-consent-body" class="mt-2 text-zinc-300">
        We use Google Analytics and Microsoft Clarity to understand which parts
        of this site help people, and which parts confuse them. Both are
        cookie-based. The Dayseam app itself ships
        <a
          class="underline decoration-zinc-500 underline-offset-2 hover:text-zinc-100 hover:decoration-zinc-300"
          href="https://github.com/dayseam/dayseam/blob/master/docs/privacy-security.md"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer">zero telemetry</a
        > regardless of what you choose here.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="flex flex-row gap-2 sm:flex-col">
      <button
        id="cookie-consent-accept"
        type="button"
        class="rounded-lg border border-strand-gold/40 bg-strand-gold/10 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-strand-gold transition hover:bg-strand-gold/20 focus:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-strand-gold"
      >
        Accept
      </button>
      <button
        id="cookie-consent-decline"
        type="button"
        class="rounded-lg border border-white/10 bg-transparent px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-zinc-300 transition hover:bg-white/5 hover:text-zinc-100 focus:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-zinc-400"
      >
        Decline
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
</aside>

<script is:inline>
  (function () {
    var STORAGE_KEY = "dayseam-cookie-consent-v1";
    var banner = document.getElementById("cookie-consent");
    var acceptBtn = document.getElementById("cookie-consent-accept");
    var declineBtn = document.getElementById("cookie-consent-decline");

    if (!banner || !acceptBtn || !declineBtn) return;

    function readChoice() {
      try {
        return window.localStorage.getItem(STORAGE_KEY);
      } catch (_) {
        return null;
      }
    }

    function writeChoice(value) {
      try {
        window.localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, value);
      } catch (_) {
        /* storage blocked: choice is session-scoped, banner re-shows next visit */
      }
    }

    function showBanner() {
      banner.hidden = false;
      // Move focus to Accept on first show — required for keyboard
      // accessibility per WAI-ARIA dialog pattern. We don't trap
      // focus inside the banner because the banner is non-modal
      // (the page below remains usable while the banner is up).
      window.requestAnimationFrame(function () {
        acceptBtn.focus();
      });
    }

    function hideBanner() {
      banner.hidden = true;
    }

    function accept() {
      writeChoice("accepted");
      hideBanner();
      // Tell <Analytics /> it can load now. Custom event keeps
      // the components decoupled — Analytics doesn't have to know
      // anything about the banner's DOM structure.
      window.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent("dayseam:consent-granted"));
    }

    function decline() {
      writeChoice("declined");
      hideBanner();
    }

    acceptBtn.addEventListener("click", accept);
    declineBtn.addEventListener("click", decline);

    // Escape-to-decline. Safer default than Escape-to-accept; if
    // the user dismisses the dialog without engaging, treat that
    // as "I didn't say yes".
    document.addEventListener("keydown", function (event) {
      if (event.key === "Escape" && !banner.hidden) {
        decline();
      }
    });

    // Footer "Cookie preferences" link reopens the banner so a
    // user can revisit their choice. We listen for clicks on any
    // anchor with href="#cookie-preferences" — the footer carries
    // it; future pages can opt in by linking to the same hash.
    document.addEventListener("click", function (event) {
      var target = event.target;
      if (!(target instanceof Element)) return;
      var anchor = target.closest('a[href="#cookie-preferences"]');
      if (!anchor) return;
      event.preventDefault();
      try {
        window.localStorage.removeItem(STORAGE_KEY);
      } catch (_) { /* private mode */ }
      showBanner();
    });

    if (readChoice() === null) {
      showBanner();
    }
  })();
</script>
